CDC publicize allergy guidelines for schools
On Wednesday, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) a series of guidelines for the treatment of children with food allergies in schools.
These are the first such directives issued by the U.S. government, because the number of school-age children with food allergies.
One in 20 children in the United States now has a food allergy.
The prevalence of food allergies among children, according to the CDC between 1997 and 2007 has increased by 18 percent.
The guidelines include information for faculty and staff at the schools to raise awareness of food allergies and how to deal with children who show allergic reactions.
It is also recommended that schools Epinephrin stock - the injection of the EpiPen brand is used most often - in order to face a potentially fatal hypersensitivity reaction.
The legislators in the federal states have recently changed the rules so that schools can keep Epinephrin easier.
The report also contains a list of typical symptoms, which are called by children who have an allergic reaction.
Children may say: "It feels as if something is on my tongue," "my mouth feels as if there is a hair," or "tickles my tongue."
